ESSORS -- t9. THE COMMANDMENT (BUYRUK): AN INTRODUCTION TO THE SACRED TEXTS OF THE KIZILBASH-ALEVI COMMUNITY -- t10. THE ABDALS OF RUM AND THE DEVELOPMENT OF COMPETING MUSLIM CONFESSIONAL IDENTITIES IN THE EARLY MODERN EASTERN BALKANS -- t11. ORTHODOX MARTYRDOM AND CONFESSIONALIZATION IN THE OTTOMAN EMPIRE, LATE FIFTEENTH-MID-SEVENTEENTH CENTURIES -- t12. CATHOLIC CONFESSIONAL LITERATURE IN THE CHRISTIAN EAST? A VIEW FROM ROME, DIYARBAKIR, AND MOUNT LEBANON, CA. 1674 -- tPART IV: POLEMICAL ENCOUNTERS IN AN INTER-IMPERIAL PERSPECTIVE -- t13. MASJED-E JAMEʿ-YE ʿABBASI: A TWELVER SHI'ITE CONGREGATIONAL MOSQUE IN THE CONTEXT OF THE DEBATE ON THE FRIDAY PRAYER IN THE SAFAVID WORLD -- t14. ON THE MARGINS OF EMPIRE: CONFESSIONALIZATION AND THE EAST SYRIAN SCHISM OF 15521 -- t15. FROM DOCTRINAL PERSUASION TO ECONOMIC THREATS: PAOLO PIROMALLI'S MISSIONARY WORK AMONG THE ARMENIANS AND HIS CONVERSION STRATEGIES1 -- t16. INTRA-ARMENIAN POLEMICS AND CONFESSION-BUILDING IN OTTOMAN CONSTANTINOPLE: THE CASE OF GĒORG MXLAYIM ŌŁLI (1681/85-1758) -- t17. ORTHODOX CONFESSION-BUILDING AND THE GREEK CHURCH BETWEEN PROTESTANTISM AND CATHOLICISM: THE MISSION OF MARQUIS NOINTEL TO THE LEVANT (1670-1673) -- tPART V: CONTEXTUAL LIMITS OF CONFESSIONAL AMBIGUITIES -- t18. CONFESSIONAL AMBIGUITY IN THE AGE OF CONFESSION-BUILDING: PHILO-ALIDISM, SUFISM AND SUNNI ISLAM IN THE OTTOMAN EMPIRE, 1400-1700 -- t19. GRAND VIZIER KOCA SINAN PASHA AND THE OTTOMAN NON-MUSLIMS -- t20. ON THE LEGAL STATUS OF YEZIDIS: LAW, GEOGRAPHY AND CONFESSION-BUILDING IN EARLY MODERN KURDISTAN (SIXTEENTHEIGHTEENTH CENTURIES) -- t21. BROKERING TRIDENTINE MARRIAGE REFORMS AND LEGAL PLURALISM IN SEVENTEENTH-CENTURY NORTHERN OTTOMAN RUMELI -- t22. SHI'ITE-IRANIAN PILGRIMS AND SAFAVID AGENTS IN HOLY SITES UNDER OTTOMAN RULE, 1690-1710 -- tAfterword: Entangled Confessionalizations-A European Perspective -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aHistorians of the early modern Ottoman Empire have long been pointing out that in the early sixteenth century the religious outlook of the sultans and the imperially sponsored hierarchy of religious scholars underwent a shift: while heretofore they had been largely unconcerned with defining, observing or enforcing a Sunni 'orthodoxy' and 'orthopraxy', they now became increasingly invested in precisely such a project. How did the understanding of what constituted a Sunni orthodoxy and orthopraxy evolve across the spectrum of Ottoman society between the fifteenth and eighteenth centuries and how did it affect various Ottoman communities? Was it by chance or perhaps due to similar social and political processes that the growing polarization between Sunnism and Shi'ism, as well as contemporaneous building of Ottoman and Safavid empires, precisely coincided with the Catholic-Protestant (and later Calvinist) polarization and the rise of confessional states in Europe? Were these contemporaneous projects of defining correct belief and/or practice in some sort of dialogue, and is this dialogue traceable in the sources left by various individuals and communities living in or passing through Ottoman domains between c. 1500 and c. 1750? The present volume explores these questions and early modern Muslim, Jewish and Christian discourses on communal belonging, 'orthodoxy' and 'orthopraxy' through the framework of a shared 'confessional age', thus obviating the top-down model of inter-confessional relations in which Christians and Jews are always seen solely as Ottoman subjects. It offers a unique perspective on Ottoman society and early modern politics of piety by approaching empire's religious groups not as homogenous blocks of 'Muslims', 'Jews' and 'Christians' but rather highlighting intra-communal diversity. By adopting a wider Eurasian perspective, contributors explore the repercussions of the developments within various Ottoman communities as far afield as the Safavid Empire, Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth, Russia, and Europe, and vice versa. The papers focus on specific people who disseminated ideas about ritual and creedal normativity and social clusters through which such ideas spread. At the same time, they also explore the limits of such normative discourses and their agents, as well as the role of alternative ideas about confessional and communal belonging informed by various forms of ambiguity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0https://www.gorgiaspress.com/open-source  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aReligion and politics. 4aHistory. 4aMiddle East. 4aTurkey & Ottoman Empire. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Turkey & Ottoman Empire.2bisacsh1 aAntov, Nikolay, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAykan, Yavuz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurak, Guy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFilipović, Nenad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGara, Eleni, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGhobrial, John-Paul A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGüngörürler, Selim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGürkan-Anar, Damla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrstić, Tijana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrstić, Tijana, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLucca, Paolo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMuntán, Emese, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOhanjanyan, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov